<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notesheet Entry</div>
<dl id="sh8013j"> <dt class="nbunit" id="sh8013j"><a name="sh8" href="#sh8013">FW Sheet 8 </a>: <a href="../../ff/fnbs/sh8all.htm#sh8013j">p. 13(j)</a></dt> <dd> <h4> Don Leary will get his own back from old grog Georgius Quartus when the goodship Johnjoys takes the wind out waterlogged Erin&apos;s King <small>color t.b.a.</small></h4> <ul class="list-inline" id="sh8013j"><li>FW 428.18ff </li><li><a href="../../flex/pD/lexpD.htm#sh8013j">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/pD/l39pD.htm#sh8013j">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#sh8013j">MS BL 47487-18</ms> </li><li>JJA 62:033 <a name="pAd13" href="../../ff/fdra/pda.htm#pDd13">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/pD/pDd13.htm#sh8013j">Draft: III&sect;1D.13</a> </li> </ul><mm class="note">Note: A pleasure steamer named the <i>John Joyce</i> sailed from D&uacute;n Laoghaire. The <i>Erin&apos;s King</i>, another pleasure steamer, also operated from the harbour (originally named Kingstown after George IV.). Joyce was sent anonymously a throwaway announcing this three-hour coastal cruise, in September 1937. He was highly amused and asked his friend Frank Budgen to check and see if it was true that the old gent was &ldquo;employing his postvital hours transportng Dubliners round the bay&rdquo; (<cite>Letters I</cite>, 397; Ellmann, p.718). </mm> <mm class="note">Original notebook: <a name="n52068b" href="n52all.htm#n52068b">N52 (VI.B.42):068(b)</a> </dd> </dd></dl>
